<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Plan UK</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#4f81bd; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 36pt; padding-bottom:4pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Written evidence </span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">submitted by Plan UK</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt"> </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt 0pt 7.5pt 13.51pt; padding-left:22.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This submission provides evidence of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">need to focus on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, especially those facing triple discrimination due to their age, gender and disability. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It provides evidence from Plan’s research and programmes in developing countries around disability, education and health in order to make recommendations for future ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tion. This submission calls for the UK government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Develop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a disability strategy </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ensure all children with disabilities have access to a quality education </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ensure all children with disabilities are protected from violence</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ensure all children with disabi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lities can meaningfully participate in the decisions that affect them </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Promote and lead on developing better data and information about the lives of children with disabilities</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt 0pt 7.5pt 13.51pt; padding-left:22.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About Plan UK </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Plan is a global children’s charity. We work with children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in 48 of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the world’s poorest countries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">across three continents </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to help them build a better future. For 76 years we’ve been taking action and standing up for every child’s righ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t to fulfil their pote</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ntial by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">giving children a healthy start in life, includin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g access to safe drinking water. Alongside</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> securing the education of girls and boys, working with communities to pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">epare for and survive disasters and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">protect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> child</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ren from abuse and exploitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We are also inspiring </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children to take a lead in decisions that affect their lives and enabling families to earn a living and plan for their children’s future.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Plan UK is a rights-based organisation and believes it is every child’s right to have a qual</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ity education. This belief </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reflects </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the statements articulated in Article 24 of the Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities which states that p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ersons with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should not be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">excluded from the general education system on the basis of d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">isabi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ersons with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have the right to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">access an inclusive, quality and free primary education and secondary education on an equal basis with others in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> communities in which they live. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Article 32 of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Convention on the Rights of Pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ople with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">calls for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">states to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that international cooperation, including international development programmes, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> inclusive of and accessib</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">le to persons with disabilities. This highlights the need for DFID to ensure a disability strategy is in place across their programmes. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Children with disabilities are often at a double disadvantage, being marginali</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed and discriminated against because of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> their age and their disability.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Children are more vulnerable as they are not yet fully developed physically or cognitively. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Girls </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and women </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in particular are at risk when </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">factors such as gender and poverty </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increase </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> vulnerabili</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ty and marginali</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ation.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is therefore a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> need for a specific focus on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">girls and boys</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> within a disability-inclusive development agenda.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Note that experiences of disadvantage are not homogeneous across all girls and boys with disabilities, but are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strongly mediated by the type of disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or example, Plan research in Sierra Leone showed th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> children with mobility impairments incurred due to war injuries suffered less discrimination than children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with epilepsy or mental impairments.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Plan receives DFID funding through a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Programme Partnership Arrangement (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PPA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Girls Education Challenge (GEC) fund project in Sierra Leone. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The evidence and recommendations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on disability integration within DFID will be framed in relation the Girls</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Education Challenge Fund. Wider research from Plan programmes contributes towards the evidence used to support the recommendations. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Plan’s DFID funded </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GEC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> programme in Sierra Leone focusses on reaching the most marginalised groups, including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The need to reach out to these groups is clear. W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e will work with 2,052 children with disabilities through partnering with Handicap International (HI), over the three years of the project. It is the largest programme HI have been involved in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for children with disabilities in Sierra Leone. DFID has said repeatedly that they class the project as innovative due to this element on disability, which reflects the lack of other projects </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">either </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">specifically targeting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or mainstreaming </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disabled groups </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in this way. </span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:22.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Children with disabilities: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">findings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">from Plan’s research </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Globally, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children with disabilities are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> more likely to experience violence and abuse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> than children without disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Research conducted in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cameroon, Ethiopia, Senegal, Uganda and Zambia </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by the African Child Policy Forum, found that the almost 1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">000 young people with disabilities had universally experienced, at a minimum, sexual harassment and emotional violence during their childhood. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The per</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">petrators of violence were often members of their extended family or their peers, making the home and school often unsafe spaces for children with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">African Child Policy Forum research found that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">across the entire sexual violence category,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> girls and boys with disabilities were equally likely to suffer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sexual violence once or twice (28% of all cases), but girls were far more likely to suffer sexual violence more than 10 times (28%) than boys (16%).</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hildren with disabilities are less </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">likely to attend school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Plan’s new </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Include Us!</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">conducted research using data from Plan’s sponsored children, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oncluded </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the following</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> about the realities faced by children with disabilities in comparison to those without:</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">they are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">substant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ially less likely to attend school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, will experience a poorer education when in school, and are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">much more likely to have had a serious illness in the last 12 months, including malnutrit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion. C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hildren with disabilities who do attend school are generally </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">likely to be overage for their grade than their non disabled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">peers;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">research shows that this is often a precursor to drop out.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Within most countries, inclusion levels for children with disabilities in schooling were highest for those with vision or hearing impairments and lowest for those with learning, physical or communication impairments. This indicates that the level of exclus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion can be linked to the type of impairment. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ore research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is required to better determine and understand the relationships between type of impairment and school access.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Plan’s baseline</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for the Girls Education Challenge Fund programme in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">five d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">istricts in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sierra Leone (to be published) found that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> girls with disabilities experience poorer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> educational outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, school attendance, and retention, than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">those without disabilities, further legitimizing the need to focus on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">girls </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and outside of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">education.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tudy from Plan Nepal showed that children with disabilities face specific challenges in accessing health and education services, due to structural, physical and attitudinal barriers</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A Plan study from West Africa </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in Togo, Sierra Leone, Niger and Guinea, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">found that stigma and discrimination against children with disabilities from parents, teachers, community members and policy-makers hinders their access to ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ucation and protection services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">imilar </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">findings were m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ade through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">research in Guatemala</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t is also crucial to note that children with disabilities are more vulnerable in disaster</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">situations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and in these contexts are at increased risk of violations of their rights to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">protection, education and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">participation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:110%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sexual and Reproductive Health and Rights (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">SRHR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">)</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Access</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to sexual and reproductive health services can be restricted for persons with disabilities. Disabled people are often assumed not to be sexually active</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are not believed if they report sexual violence, and are often not appropriately involved in decisions about their sexual and reproductive health</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">People with learning disabilities and difficulties can face additional or heightened risks: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, higher</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> risks of sexual abuse, assault and rape</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> lower access to services, support, or redress, and forced sterilisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">isabled children are also much more likely to suffer sexual violence and girls with disabilities are even more vulnerable.</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Furthermore l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ack of access to sexual and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reproductive health</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> services has greater impact upon girls and women.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For every woman who dies as a result of pregnancy related complications, some twenty others face serious or long-lasting consequences.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Harmful practices such</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">female genital mutilation (FGM), early and forced marriage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, as well as poor sexual and reproductive health including high </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and frequent fertility can result</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in disabilities including obstetric fistula and uterine prolapse.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Currently an estimated 2 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">million women in Asia and Sub Saharan Africa live with untreated fistula.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ccording to a WHO multi-country study of 30,000 women on the obstetric effects of FGM, the relative risk of adverse maternal outcomes increased for women with FGM I, II or II as co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mpared to women without FGM. Risks seem to be greater with more extensive FGM.</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sexual Violence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The risk of depression and anxiety</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is three to four times higher for those who have experienced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gender-based violence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and around a third of all survivors of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rape experience </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Posttraumatic Stress Disorder</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Sexual violence can result in acute and chronic physical disabilities, for example </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">severe pain during menstruation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or prolonged menstrual bleeding, as well as long term </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">genital-anal trauma</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sexually trans</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mitted infections</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Integration of disability issues within </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Plan UK’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> funded education programmes</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Plan UK recognises the work DFID has done on disability in the last 10 years, DFID’s work has placed the issue on the global development agenda. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This would be strengthened by a strategy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the integration of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">issues </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">across all its projects.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> DFID’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> recent commitments on disability are welcomed by Plan UK as they are an important signal to developing country partners and other donors to pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ioritise disabled people. Plan has seen this commitment through its GEC programme funding. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Plan’s GEC programme interventions focus on poor rural girls, within this group, girls with disabilities are more marginalised with 76% estimated to be out of scho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ol</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> due to discrimination, stigma and a lack of inclusive education opportunities, adequately trained teachers or accessible facilities. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Community Based Rehabilitation (CBR) approach involves the whole community to foster educational inclusion. Disab</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ility will be mainstreamed through all interventions and accessibility needs addressed in terms of materials, communication and venue selection where relevant. It is assumed that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are even l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ess likely to reach the end of p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rimary S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chool and make the transition to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">junior secondary school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and therefore most of the direct support for disabled children with focus on their enrolling/re-enrolling in Primary.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are early on in the programme but we have some lessons learnt already, including that working with children with disabilities in a rural setting is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resource intensive exercise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> than anticipated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Children with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are often </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hidden by famil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ies, and to ensu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re their specific needs are met requires specialist expertise and raising community awareness of  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rights</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of children with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Case Study:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Children with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> pushed out of school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. One </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">child with disability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in Kailahun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Sierra Leone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was a girl </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with albinism </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who had </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a visual impairment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. She was no longer in school. She had hoped to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pass junior secondary school three</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and was determined to make it as far as the disability would allow. Then, she got pregnant. She told her </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">interviewer, “Yes I have been mistreated sexually and physically and also insulted by my teachers and colleagues in school. When I decided to leave school it was because I was impregnated by some guys I didn't know. Because of my poor eyesight I can’t reme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mber them, so they denied responsibility.” After she became pregnant the school refused to let her continue.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Data: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">number </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">girls with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reported in Plan’s baseline household survey </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">likely to be much lower than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in reality</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his reflect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s the lack of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">data available on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, due to their exclusion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the underreporting by community members due to stigma and lack of awareness. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.4pt; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Attitudes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Plan’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">baseline survey</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for the GEC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">was a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lso revealing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">around </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">non disabled schoo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l age </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">girls’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">attitudes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of children with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> majority of girls believe it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is okay for children who have d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">isabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">go to school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. 23</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">% of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">girls who have physical disabilities believe that it is okay for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">girls like themsel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ves </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> get an education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This might indicate the way </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are treated in school,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">if their colleagues do not believe it is important for them to be there, and more than that, are contributing to  perception of themselves as not worthy of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">being at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">school.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This also illustrates the wider community’s perceptions of the value and capabiliti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of children with disabilities,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> much of the internalisation of these perceptions will start at a young age</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. And </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">demonstrates the importance of home and family </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and thee need for parents to accept disabled children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hang</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> attitudes and stig</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ma </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of parents i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s the first step to inclusion. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Children with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">face</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> discrimination and abuse in school </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Nearly every single child with disability  interviewed in each district </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">identified </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">verbal and physical harassment as  the main reason for lea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ving school. Many also said that they (or their parents) had brought the abuse to their teachers’ attention, but intervention (if any) had been ineffective. A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">girl with disability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in Moyamba noted “only my colleagues would disturb and mock me. I do report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to the teachers so the teacher </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in return will flog the people. M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y colleagues laugh at me because I am unable to talk, so that made me drop out of school.” Some</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> children with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> even described abuse from the teachers themselves</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ecommendations for action </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Overall recommendation: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Plan </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is calling for DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">develop an overarching disability inclusive development strategy</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with focus areas including access to quality education, protection from violence and meaningful participation in decisions and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">across its work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to focus on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">those most vulnerable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as a result of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">intersecting inequalities incl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uding gender and poverty.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disability strategy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Plan UK supports the recommendations made by the Global Campaign for Education and the Bond Disability and Development group for DFID to implement a twin-track approach to disability which would involve: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">acti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ve inclusion of disabled people in all aspects of development (For example: education programmes that include  girls</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and boys</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with disabilities, elimination of violence against women and girls programmes that include women  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and girls </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with disabilities by r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecognising and addressing the issues that affect them)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Specific inputs which support the empowerment and development opportunities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of persons with disabilities (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for example Community Based Rehabilitation programs, support formation and networking of Disabl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed People Organisations-DPOs) . </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Development of such a strategy must be done through a process of consultation with persons with disabilities, including children. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ensure c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">hildren with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">have access </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">quality </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">education. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A quality education is one that is grounded in respect for human rights and gender equity, that is accessible to all children without discrimination, and one in which all children are encouraged to fulfil their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">capabilities.  It includes a learning environ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ment that is learner-friendly, safe and healthy for all children with mechanisms to prevent and respond to violence.  A quality education is accountable to children through the participation of children, families and communities in school governance and de</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cision –making. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Activities required to ensure this include </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">training</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> teachers to ensure they can support the education of children with disabilities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">urriculum adaptation and improved accessibility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are also required</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, alongside raising public awar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eness on the rights to quality education for all children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and initiatives to challenge discrimination against children with disabilities within the school community</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Children with disabilities should also have access to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">early childhood care and development </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(ECCD), which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">shown to provide immense benefits for children throughout life</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">help them </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reach their full potential</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Inclusive ECCD is also a critical pathway to education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> alongside the resources, both mat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">erial and capacity building needed to integrate inclusive education into all teacher training</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">All </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">children with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> are p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rotect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ed from violence:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> both within a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd outside of school contexts, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ights </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hildren with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to protection from violence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ust be secured. P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rotection </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">systems</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">need to be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> resourced to focus on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and be accessible to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the most vulnerable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">All </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">children with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">meaningfully participate in decisions that affect them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unless girls and boys w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ith disabilities are consulted and involved in the design, implementation and monitoring of interventions across all sectors then </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the interventions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will not meet their needs and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will be left behind.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Improve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> collection</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID’s focus on the data revolution can be used to address the paucity of data on children with disabilities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Plan supports the recommendation made by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UNICEF in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">he</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">State of the World’s Children: Children with Disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that for children with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">many of their deprivations stem from and are perpetuated by their invisibility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">… </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there is a need for research to render more children visible by improvi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng data collection and analysis’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Research </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on people with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should be disaggr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">egated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">age, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gender</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, location, wealth quintile and type of impairment. This data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should be used to track the progress of disadvantaged and marginalised groups across all goals, targets and indicators</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> within the post-2015 framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he negotiations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">around the post-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2015 development framework are a key moment for the UK government, DFID and FCO to push for this change to data collection within the framework.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style=